      "content": "Identifying racial stereotypes in Hollywood is crucial for writing responsible satire, as missteps can easily backfire or alienate audiences. Common tropes include the \"mammy\" figure, the \"sassy sidekick,\" and the straight-man comic, all of which have deep historical roots in systemic racism and are often considered offensive today. While satire can critique these flaws, it is generally safer to avoid reinforcing them ironically, as the line between mockery and offense often becomes muddled. Instead, focusing contemporary awards on irrelevant production staff or mocking the industry's obsession with superficiality can achieve your comedic goals without relying on harmful caricatures. Prioritizing humor that highlights real-world hypocrisy rather than repeating old jokes will make your script both smarter and more inclusive.",
